english:
  title: Two Poems Following the Rhyme of Cheonsu Temple
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The wall crumbles, the foundation stones shatter, fireflies glow in the dark—
    All that remains is for the people of the capital to point and turn back.
    Like the cry of a celestial crane across a thousand years,
    The mountains and rivers endure as before, yet the ancient people are gone.

    Spring winds scatter blossoms everywhere—
    As if I ride a lone horse toward Songdo to return.
    When we speak of the notable figures of five hundred years,
    Who truly bears the blame for leading the king astray and ruining the realm?
  footnotes:
    - 'Cheonsu Temple: A Buddhist temple associated with historical Korean capitals, here evoking the passage of time and dynastic change.'
    - 'Songdo: The traditional name for Kaesong, the capital of Goryeo, suggesting nostalgia for a lost golden age.'
    - The poem appears to meditate on historical ruin and moral accountability, possibly reflecting on the fall of a dynasty or the consequences of corrupt leadership.
